          Key Opta stats compiled by the world game: - Troy Deeney became the fourth player to score in 100 matches for Watford in all competitions, after Tommy Barnett, Ross Jenkins and Luther Blissett. - This was the first time that Tottenham lost a game in which they had been leading in the Premier League since November 2016 against eventual champions Chelsea, ending a run of 48 league matches without defeat when taking the lead at any stage. - This was Watford's first league win over Tottenham since May 1987, ending a run of 12 league games without a victory over the Lilywhites (D4 L8). - Since Javier Gracia took over as Watford manager in January, no side has won more home Premier League games than the Hornets (seven, level with Arsenal, Liverpool, Manchester City, Manchester United and Spurs).

        • [ - ] Castle - member since 08-Sep-15

          Tottenham have done well not dropping points so far and they seem to be getting better after destroying United. Lucas Moura has impressed so far, he's their biggest goal threat at the moment and he can press very effectively up front. Also Alli and Kane are back at their best surprisingly fast. Tottenham will surely continue with back four, but Davies could return and Aurier could also come in for Trippier who had a knock against United and should be rested anyway since he played a lot at World Cup. Watford are in great form and home fixture gives them a good chance for draw at least. However, they had their difficulties against Palace and the match could have ended also as a draw had Palace been sharper with their chances in the first half. I'd expect Tottenham to convert their opportunities better and win with one or two goal marching, so 1-2 or 1-3.
